@paper-source /home/joe/npt/paper-v2.3/paper_v2.3.html
@merge-policy Preserve the canonical account of protected conditions for iterative competence while retaining the paper variant's delivery-profile mechanism and network-property coverage frame.

! conclusion: Training delivery succeeds only when a trainer's declared delivery profile is matched by institutional provisioning. The breadth of open-research topics should be treated as a network coverage property, not as a demand on every individual. Without protected time, administrative backing, manageable scope, and team support, the trainer absorbs a structural coordination problem as personal overload.
  + context: A programme trains intermediaries who are expected to deliver locally across a broad open-research territory. Delivery depends on trainer competence, but also on institutional conditions: rooms, protected time, administrative support, clear role mandate, and manageable scope. In NPT terms this combines Collective Action 3.3 Skill Set Workability and 3.4 Contextual Integration. In Ostrom terms this is the provisioning problem: resources must be supplied rather than assumed. In the paper's tier language this is an intervention-tier, medium-coordination pattern requiring at least the programme and an Institutional Lead or local representative.
  + IF:
    A trained intermediary has internalised the programme scaffold and is ready to develop local competence through delivery. They need to deliver, iterate, fail, adjust, and develop practical judgement in their setting. The topic landscape is wider than any single trainer's primary expertise, and many trainers are professional staff delivering outside their main discipline.
  + HOWEVER:
    The institution provides no protected conditions for iteration, and the programme has no declared delivery profiles. Sessions try to cover everything, crowding out interaction and depth. Trainers report inadequate preparation and impostor syndrome (FG1.15, FG2A.13; FG3.13, FG2A.4; T2A: "I didn't feel prepared to talk about all the areas"; T3: "There's a little bit of impostor syndrome"). They absorb four to six roles that the programme design distributes across actors: trainer, materials adapter, marketer, evaluator, local coordinator. The breadth gap is structural even when individual psychological ability is high (COM-B "I am psychologically able" M=4.85).
  + THEN:
    Each trainer declares a delivery profile: the modules they will own and the limits of that ownership. Each participating institution commits an explicit coverage profile with named resourcing: protected time, rooms, IT/admin support, team coverage, and a manageable delivery scope. The programme publishes aggregate coverage across the network so gaps are visible to the programme, not only to individual trainers. Coverage becomes a distributed property of the network rather than an invisible expectation placed on each person.
  + BECAUSE:
    NPT: Skill Set Workability is the fit between work demands and what the trainer can reasonably do; Contextual Integration is the fit between the work and the institution's resources. Breadth overload breaks both.

    Sen: The conversion at stake is temporal and organisational. Informational clarity from Pattern 1 does not become competence unless the trainer has the time and conditions to iterate.

    Whole-board play: AlphaZero could not learn by reading about Go; it needed games. The trainer has far fewer games, so each delivery event must be protected enough to be formative. Rushed, overpacked, undersupported, or one-off sessions do not let local competence develop.

    Ostrom: The action situation works only when the relevant resources are provisioned. Where the institutional resource is absent, the individual fills a structural gap and practice survives only as long as they do.
  + NEXT-STEPS:
    - Ask each trainer to declare the modules they will own
    - Ask each institution to commit a coverage profile with named resourcing
    - Define the minimum support package: time, space, admin, team support, scope
    - Publish aggregate coverage across the network so gaps are visible
    - Audit breadth-vs-depth where trainers cover outside their declared profile
    - Test: can every trainer deliver without absorbing roles that should be distributed?
  + INVARIANT-STATEMENT:
    Each trainer has a declared delivery profile. Each participating institution has a committed coverage profile with protected time, administrative backing, and manageable scope. The programme maintains a current view of coverage as a network property.
  + FAILURE-MODES:
    - Breadth overload: trainers cover topics outside their expertise without support
    - Impostor-driven delivery: trainer reaches the room under-prepared because profile declaration was impossible
    - No iteration: trainer delivers once and never develops local competence
    - Role overload: trainer absorbs roles designed for distinct actors
    - Un-profiled institutions: institution participates without naming coverage aims or resourcing
    - Per-trainer coverage requirement: network coverage is treated as an individual requirement
    - Goodwill-dependent delivery: practice survives only while the individual persists
  + ANCESTORS:
    - Paper v2.3, Pattern 2: Protected Interaction
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T1 ("give it more time than you expect")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2A ("I didn't feel prepared to talk about all the areas")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T3 ("There's a little bit of impostor syndrome")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B.17 (delivers only a fraction of material learned)
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T2B ("the amount of rooms we can book is a big issue")
    - UKRN T3 transcript: T3 ("I'm more or less a single person")
    - Focus-group codes: FG1.15, FG2A.13, FG3.13, FG2A.4
    - COM-B: "I am psychologically able" M=4.85
  + DERIVATION:
    Derived from NPT Collective Action 3.3 Skill Set Workability and 3.4 Contextual Integration.
    Tier: Intervention. Coordination: Medium (programme + institutional representative).
    Implementation-mode link: weak coordination produces absorbed input; supported team-working contributes to multiplied input.
    Canonical deepening: protected iteration as the condition for competence development.
    Paper-specific mechanism: declared delivery profiles and institutional coverage as a network property.
